var glossary = new Array();
//       ALPHA/DISPLAY INDEX (A first - Z last), HEADING (not used), TERM, DEFINITION
glossary[0] = new Array( "A","","Absent Without Leave","<p>AWOL is a non-pay status that covers an absence from duty which has not been approved.</p>\n<p><em>(Source:&nbsp;U.S. Office of Personnel Management)</em></p>");
glossary[1] = new Array( "A","","Affirmative Employment Plan ","<p>Written plans for programs required by Executive Order 11478 and other laws and regulations that prohibit employment discrimination based on race, color, religion, sex, national origin, handicap, or age, and require agencies to promote the full realization of equal employment opportunity through a continuing affirmative program. Affirmative Employment Plans (AEPs) may contain workforce analysis of the distribution of each group compared to the benchmark, noting any areas where the group has a low participation rate. The AEP may include goals and timetables for addressing any identified barriers to full participation.</p>\n<p><em>(Source: VA Office of Diversity and Inclusion)</em></p>");
glossary[2] = new Array( "A","","Annual Leave","<p>Annual leave is provided to allow employees extended leave for rest and recreation and to provide periods of time off for personal and emergency purposes.</p>\n<p><em>(Source: 2017 Master Agreement; Article 17, Section 2A)</em></p>");
glossary[3] = new Array( "A","","AWOL","<p>Absent without leave</p>");
glossary[4] = new Array( "B","","Bargaining Unit","<p>A group of employees for whom a labor union negotiates a collective bargaining agreement.</p>\n<p><em>(Source: Merriam-Webster dictionary)</em></p>");
glossary[5] = new Array( "B","","Bargaining Unit Employee","<p>A bargaining unit employee for purposes of&nbsp;this eLearning curriculum is an employee included in a bargaining unit consolidated and certified by the Federal Labor Relations Authority (FLRA) on Certificate Number 22-07730 (UC) and any successor certificates.</p>\n<p><em>(Source: 2017 Master Agreement; Article 1, Section 1A)</em></p>");
glossary[6] = new Array( "B","","Basic Pay","<p>Basic Pay is defined as the rate of pay fixed by applicable law or regulation.</p>\n<p><em>(Source:&nbsp;U.S. Office of Personnel Management)</em></p>");
glossary[7] = new Array( "C","","Collective Bargaining","<p>Collective bargaining is negotiation between an employer and a labor union usually on wages, hours, and working conditions.</p>\n<p><em>(Source: Merriam-Webster dictionary)</em></p>");
glossary[8] = new Array( "C","","Commercial Activity","<p>Office of Management and Budget Circular No. A-76 defines a commercial activity as a recurring service that could be performed by&nbsp;the private sector and is resourced, performed, and controlled by the agency through performance&nbsp;by government personnel, a contract, or a fee-for-service agreement. A commercial activity is not&nbsp;so intimately related to the public interest as to mandate performance by government personnel.&nbsp;Commercial activities may be found within, or throughout, organizations that perform inherently&nbsp;governmental activities or classified work.</p>\n<p><em>(Source:&nbsp;Office of Management and Budget)</em></p>");
glossary[9] = new Array( "C","","Compensation Panel","<p>A compensation panel is a group of physicians or dentists responsible for evaluating the services of physicians or dentists and making recommendations for pay to an approving department official.</p>\n<p><em>(Source:&nbsp;VA Handbook 5007/32, Part IX)</em></p>");
glossary[10] = new Array( "C","","Compensatory Time Off","<p>Compensatory time off is time off with pay in lieu of overtime pay for irregular or occasional overtime work.</p>\n<p><em>(Source: U.S. Office of Personnel Management)</em></p>");
glossary[11] = new Array( "C","","Compensatory Time Off for Travel","<p>Compensatory time off for travel is earned by an employee for time spent in a travel status away from the employee\'s official duty station when such time is not otherwise compensable.</p>\n<p><em>(Source: U.S. Office of Personnel Management)</em></p>");
glossary[12] = new Array( "C","","Competency","<p>A competency is a measurable pattern of knowledge, skills, abilities, behaviors, and other characteristics that an individual needs to perform work roles or occupational functions successfully. Competencies specify the \"how\" of performing job tasks, or what the person needs to do the job successfully.</p>\n<p><em>(Source: U.S. Office of Personnel Management)</em></p>");
glossary[13] = new Array( "C","","Competitive Area","<p>When discussing a Reduction in Force, a Competitive Area is an area in which employees compete for retention. A Competitive Area must be defined solely in terms of the Department&rsquo;s organizational services or units and geographical location, and it must include all employees within the Competitive Area.</p>\n<p><em>(Source: 2017 Master Agreement; Article 61, Section 5C)</em></p>");
glossary[14] = new Array( "C","","Competitive Level","<p>When used in reference to a Reduction in Force, Competitive Levels are positions in a Competitive Area that are in the same grade (or occupational level) and classification series that are so alike in qualification requirements, duties, pay schedule, and working conditions that the incumbent of one position can successfully perform the critical elements of any other position in the level upon assignment to it without undue interruption is known as a Competitive Level. Competitive Levels for Title 38 employees will be determined in accordance within VA Directive and Handbook 5005.</p>\n<p><em>(Source: 2017 Master Agreement; Article 61, Section 5D)</em></p>");
glossary[15] = new Array( "C","","Conditions of Employment","<p>Conditions of employment means personnel policies, practices, and matters, whether established by rule, regulation, or otherwise, affecting working conditions.</p>\n<p><em>(Source: 5 USC 7103)</em></p>");
glossary[16] = new Array( "C","","Convening Authority","<p>The authority responsible for convening and supervising administrative investigations under VA&nbsp;Directive 0700. Convening Authorities include the heads of VA Administrations and Staff Offices, chief executives of VA facilities, and authorities senior to any of them in the VA organization.</p>\n<p><em>(Source:&nbsp;VA Handbook 0700)</em></p>");
glossary[17] = new Array( "D","","DAB","<p>Disciplinary Appeals Board</p>");
glossary[18] = new Array( "D","","Demonstration Project","<p>A project conducted by the Office of Personnel Management or under its supervision to determine whether a specified change in personnel management policies and procedures would result in improved Federal personnel management.</p>\n<p><em>(Source: 2017 Master Agreement; Article 34, Section 1B)</em></p>");
glossary[19] = new Array( "D","","Department Official","<p><span style=\"background-color: #ffffff;\">For purposes of this eLearning curriculum, a Department Official is an individual employed by the Department and acting in a representational role for the Agency.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"background-color: #ffffff;\"><em>(Source: derived by the LMR-NAGE eLearning Curriculum Team from the definition of Management Official in VA Directive 5023)</em></span></p>");
glossary[20] = new Array( "D","","Department, The","<p>The United States Department of Veterans Affairs</p>");
glossary[21] = new Array( "D","","Desk Audit","<p>A desk audit is conducted when an employee and supervisor are interviewed to obtain information about the kind and difficulty of the work the employee is doing.</p>\n<p><em>(Source: U.S. Office of Personnel Management)</em></p>");
glossary[22] = new Array( "D","","Detail","<p>A detail is the temporary assignment of an employee to a different position for a specified period of time with the employee returning to his regular duties at the end of the detail.</p>\n<p><em>(Source: 2017 Master Agreement; Article 25, Section 1)</em></p>");
glossary[23] = new Array( "D","","Disciplinary Appeals Board","<p>A three-member board designated to hear a Title 38 employee&rsquo;s appeal of a major adverse action taken that is based on a question of the employee\'s professional conduct or competence.</p>\n<p><em>Also known as: Title 38 Disciplinary Appeals Board</em></p>\n<p><em>(Source: VA Handbook 5021/10)</em></p>");
glossary[24] = new Array( "D","","Dues","<p><span style=\"background-color: #ffffff;\">A regular payment of money made by members of a union to that union.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"background-color: #ffffff;\"><em>(Source: adapted from Wikipedia - Union Dues for the purposes of this LMR-NAGE eLearning Curriculum)</em></span></p>");
glossary[25] = new Array( "D","","Duty Station","<p><span style=\"background-color: #ffffff;\">The VA facility in which an employee works.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"background-color: #ffffff;\"><em>(Source: LMR-NAGE eLearning Curriculum Team)</em></span></p>");
glossary[26] = new Array( "D","","Duty to Bargain","<p>Obligation to bargain between the Parties</p>\n<p><em>(Source: 5 USC 7117)&nbsp;</em></p>");
glossary[27] = new Array( "E","","EEO","<p>Equal Employment Opportunity</p>");
glossary[28] = new Array( "E","","EEOC","<p>The U.S. Equal Employment Opportunity Commission</p>");
glossary[29] = new Array( "E","","Electronic Official Personnel Folder","<p>An electronic version of the paper OPF and a system for accessing the electronic folder online. The eOPF system combines document management with workflow capabilities. The eOPF allows each employee to have an electronic personnel folder instead of a paper folder. Benefits of eOPF include: immediate access to personnel forms and information for a geographically dispersed workforce; e-mail notification to employee when documents are added to their eOPF; multi-level secure environment with security rules for sensitive information; no loss of official personnel documents due to filing and routing errors; reduced costs associated with storage, maintenance, and retrieval of records; electronic transfer of human resources (HR) data; integration with agency&rsquo;s human resources information systems (HRIS); and compliance with OPM and federally mandated HR employee record management regulations.</p>\n<p><em>(Source: U.S. Office of Personnel Management)</em></p>");
glossary[30] = new Array( "E","","Employee","<p>Employee beginning with a capital E is a convention specific to this eLearning curriculum. It provides a&nbsp;shortened version of the term \"Bargaining Unit Employee\" for purpose<span style=\"background-color: #ffffff;\">s of this training.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"background-color: #ffffff;\"><em>(Source: LMR-NAGE eLearning Curriculum Team)</em></span></p>");
glossary[31] = new Array( "E","","eOPF","<p>Electronic Official Personnel Folder</p>");
glossary[32] = new Array( "E","","Equal Employment Opportunity","<p><span style=\"background-color: #ffffff;\">Policy that provides equal employment opportunity to all employees and applicants for employment without discrimination including workplace harassment, based on race, color, religion, national origin, sex (including gender identity, transgender status, sexual orientation, and pregnancy), age, disability, genetic information, marital/parental status, political affiliation, or retaliation for opposing discriminatory practices or for participating in the discrimination-complaint process.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"background-color: #ffffff;\" data-mce-mark=\"1\"><em>(Source: U.S. Department of Veterans Affairs;&nbsp;VHA Directive 1124, Equal Opportunity Policy)</em></span></p>");
glossary[33] = new Array( "E","","Equal Employment Opportunity Commission, U.S. ","<p>The U.S. Equal Employment Opportunity Commission (EEOC) is responsible for enforcing federal laws that make it illegal to discriminate against a job applicant or an employee because of the person\'s race, color, religion, sex (including pregnancy, gender identity, and sexual orientation), national origin, age (40 or older), disability or genetic information. It is also illegal to discriminate against a person because the person complained about discrimination, filed a charge of discrimination, or participated in an employment discrimination investigation or lawsuit.</p>\n<p><em>(Source:&nbsp;U.S. Equal Employment&nbsp;Opportunity Commission)</em></p>");
glossary[34] = new Array( "E","","Excused Absence","<p><span style=\"background-color: #ffffff;\">Any absence covered by leave.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"background-color: #ffffff;\"><em>(Source: LMR-NAGE eLearning Curriculum Team)</em></span></p>");
glossary[35] = new Array( "F","","Family and Medical Leave Act of 1993","<p>The Family and Medical Leave Act (FMLA) provides certain employees with one full year of service with up to 12 weeks of unpaid, job-protected leave per year. It also requires that their group health benefits be maintained during the leave. This leave is used to care for an immediate family member (spouse, child, or parent) with a serious health condition.</p>\n<p><em>(Source: Family and Medical Leave Act of 1993)</em></p>");
glossary[36] = new Array( "F","","Federal Labor Relations Authority, U.S. ","<p>The U.S. Federal Labor Relations Authority (FLRA) is an independent administrative federal agency created by Title VII of the Civil Service Reform Act of 1978, also known as the Federal Service Labor-Management Relations Statute (the Statute), 5 USC Chapter 71. The FLRA\'s mission: The FLRA promotes stable, constructive labor-management relations through the resolution and prevention of labor disputes in a manner that gives full effect to the collective-bargaining rights of employees, unions, and agencies.</p>\n<p><em>(Source:&nbsp;U.S. Federal Labor Relations Authority)</em></p>");
glossary[37] = new Array( "F","","Federal Mediation and Conciliation Service","<p>The Federal Mediation and Conciliation Service, created in 1947, is an independent agency whose mission is to preserve and promote labor-management peace and cooperation. The agency provides mediation and conflict resolution services to industry, government agencies, and communities.</p>\n<p><em>(Source:&nbsp;Federal Mediation and Conciliation Service)</em></p>");
glossary[38] = new Array( "F","","FLRA","<p>U.S. Federal Labor Relations Authority</p>");
glossary[39] = new Array( "F","","FMCS","<p>Federal Mediation and Conciliation Service</p>");
glossary[40] = new Array( "F","","FMLA","<p>Family and Medical Leave Act of 1993</p>");
glossary[41] = new Array( "F","","FTEE","<p>Full-time employee equivalent</p>");
glossary[42] = new Array( "F","","Full-Time Employee Equivalent","<p>A full-time employee equivalent, or FTEE, is the hours worked by one employee on a full-time basis. On an annual basis, an FTEE is considered to be 2,080 hours.</p>\n<p><em>(Source: LMR-NAGE eLearning Curriculum Team)</em></p>");
glossary[43] = new Array( "F","","Furlough","<p>In the context of the master agreement, furlough refers to a specific type of furlough: an administrative furlough.</p>\n<p>An administrative furlough is a planned event by an agency which is designed to absorb reductions necessitated by downsizing, reduced funding, lack of work, or any budget situation other than a lapse in appropriations. Furloughs that would potentially result from sequestration would generally be considered administrative furloughs.</p>\n<p><em>(Source: U.S. Office of Personnel Management)</em></p>");
glossary[44] = new Array( "G","","Grievable","<p><span style=\"background-color: #ffffff;\">An adjective that describes a complaint that is eligible for the grievance process.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"background-color: #ffffff;\"><em>(Source: derived from definition of \"grievance\" in 5 USC 7103(a)(9))</em></span></p>");
glossary[45] = new Array( "G","","Grievance","<p>A grievance under 5 USC 7103(a)(9) means any complaint:<br>&nbsp; A. by an employee concerning any matter relating to the employment of the employee;<br>&nbsp; B. by the Union concerning any matter relating to employment of an employee; or,<br>&nbsp; C. by any employee, the Union or the Department concerning:<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;1. the effect or interpretation, or a claim of breach of this Agreement; or,<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;2. any claimed violation, misinterpretation, or misapplication of any law, rule, or regulation affecting conditions of employment.</p>\n<p><em>(Source: 5 USC 7103(a)(9))&nbsp;</em></p>");
glossary[46] = new Array( "G","","Grieve","<p>Act of filling a grievance according to Article 40: Grievance Procedure.</p>\n<p><em>(Source: Derived from definition of \"grievance\" in 5 USC 7103(a)(9))</em></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>");
glossary[47] = new Array( "H","","Health Care System","<p><span style=\"background-color: #ffffff;\">In many areas of the country, several medical centers and clinics may work together to offer services to area Veterans as a Healthcare System (HCS) in an effort to provide more efficient care. By sharing services between medical centers, Healthcare Systems allow VHA to provide Veterans easier access to advanced medical care closer to their homes.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"background-color: #ffffff;\"><em>(Source: U.S. Department of Veterans Affairs; VHA Website, About VHA)</em></span></p>");
glossary[48] = new Array( "H","","Hours of Duty","<p>The hours in which an employee is performing their work duties.</p>\n<p><em>Also known as: Hours of Work</em></p>\n<p><em>(Source: LMR-NAGE eLearning Curriculum&nbsp;Team)&nbsp;</em></p>");
glossary[49] = new Array( "H","","Hours of Work","<p>The hours in which an employee is performing their work duties.</p>\n<p><em>Also known as: Hours of Duty</em></p>\n<p><em>(Source: LMR-NAGE eLearning Curriculum Team)</em></p>");
glossary[50] = new Array( "H","","Hybrid Title 38 Bargaining Unit Employee","<p>Hybrid Title 38 Bargaining Unit Employees&nbsp;are employees covered by Title 38 for their appointment, advancement, and certain pay matters. They are covered by Title 5 for other aspects of employment such as performance appraisal, leave, hours of duty, adverse actions, probationary period, reemployment rights, reduction-in-force rules, and retirement rules. Examples of positions are licensed practical nurses, pharmacists, and physical therapists. The full list is found in 38 USC 7401(3).</p>\n<p><em>Also known as: Hybrid Title 38 Employee</em></p>\n<p><em>(Source: 2017 Master Agreement; Article 62, Section 1)</em></p>");
glossary[51] = new Array( "H","","Hybrid Title 38 Employee","<p>Hybrid Title 38 Employees are employees covered by Title 38 for their appointment, advancement, and certain pay matters. They are covered by Title 5 for other aspects of employment such as performance appraisal, leave, hours of duty, adverse actions, probationary period, reemployment rights, reduction-in-force rules, and retirement rules. Examples of positions are licensed practical nurses, pharmacists, and physical therapists. The full list is found in 38 USC 7401(3).</p>\n<p><em>Also known as:&nbsp;Hybrid Title 38 Bargaining Unit Employees</em></p>\n<p><em>(Source: 2017 Master Agreement; Article 62, Section 1)</em></p>");
glossary[52] = new Array( "I","","Incapacitated","<p><span style=\"background-color: #ffffff;\">Temporarily or permanently impaired by mental and/or physical deficiency, disability, illness, or use of drugs to the extent of lacking sufficient understanding to make rational decisions or engage in responsible actions.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"background-color: #ffffff;\"><em>(Source: Business Dictionary Website, \"What is legally <span style=\"font-size: 12px;\">incapacitated</span>?\" definition)</em></span></p>");
glossary[53] = new Array( "I","","In-Service Occupational Exam","<p>An exam performed to ensure a potential employee meets the standards required to perform the duties of a specific position.</p>\n<p><em>(Source: LMR-NAGE eLearning Curriculum Team)&nbsp;</em></p>");
glossary[54] = new Array( "L","","Leave Without Pay","<p>A temporary non-pay status and absence from duty that, in most cases, is granted at the employee\'s request. In most instances, granting leave without pay is a matter of supervisory discretion and may be limited by VA policies. Extended leave without pay can have effects on Federal benefits and programs which can be viewed on the U.S. Office of Personnel Management website.</p>\n<p><em>(Source:&nbsp;U.S. Office of Personnel Management)</em></p>");
glossary[55] = new Array( "L","","Local Agreement","<p>A term that encompasses existing local supplemental agreements and locally negotiated memoranda of understanding (MOUs.)</p>\n<p><span data-mce-mark=\"1\"><em>(Source: LMR-NAGE eLearning Curriculum Team)</em></span><span style=\"background-color: #ffff99;\" data-mce-mark=\"1\"><em><br></em></span></p>");
glossary[56] = new Array( "L","","Local Bargaining","<p><span style=\"background-color: #ffffff;\">Bargaining that takes place at the local level.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"background-color: #ffffff;\"><em>(Source: LMR-NAGE eLearning Curriculum Team)</em></span></p>");
glossary[57] = new Array( "L","","Local Supplemental Agreement","<p><span style=\"background-color: #ffffff;\">A locally negotiated supplemental agreement to the Master Agreement.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"background-color: #ffffff;\"><em>(Source: LMR-NAGE eLearning Curriculum Team)</em></span></p>");
glossary[58] = new Array( "L","","Local, The","<p><span style=\"background-color: #ffffff;\">The local NAGE office; a shortened version of Local Union.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"background-color: #ffffff;\"><em>(Source: LMR-NAGE eLearning Curriculum Team)</em></span></p>");
glossary[59] = new Array( "L","","LSA","<p>local supplemental agreement</p>");
glossary[60] = new Array( "L","","LWOP","<p>Leave without Pay</p>");
glossary[61] = new Array( "M","","Master Agreement Practitioner","<p><span style=\"background-color: #ffffff;\">A term specific to this eLearning curriculum to identify VA employees who, as a part of their job duties, interpret and provide guidance on the articles of the Master Agreement. These may include Supervisors, Department Officials, Human Resources staff, or Union Representatives.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"background-color: #ffffff;\"><em>(Source: LMR-NAGE eLearning Curriculum Team)</em></span></p>");
glossary[62] = new Array( "M","","MCD","<p>Medical Center Director</p>");
glossary[63] = new Array( "M","","Medical Center Director","<p><span style=\"background-color: #ffffff;\">The Medical Center Director has the full delegated authority and responsibility for executive level management of a VA Medical Center (VAMC). The Director has overall responsibility for planning, organizing, coordinating, controlling, reviewing, evaluating, and improving the medical, administrative, and support operations of the facility.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"background-color: #ffffff;\"><em>(Source: U.S. Department of Veterans Affairs Website; Careers)</em></span></p>");
glossary[64] = new Array( "M","","Medical Review Officer","<p>A licensed physician who reviews, verifies, and reports a specimen test result to a federal agency.</p>\n<p><em>(Source:&nbsp;VA Handbook 5383)</em></p>");
glossary[65] = new Array( "M","","Memorandum of Understanding","<p><span style=\"background-color: #ffffff;\">A memorandum of understanding (MOU) is a national or local level agreement between the Department and NAGE. MOUs are normally the product of Mid-Term Bargaining.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"background-color: #ffffff;\"><em>(Source: LMR-NAGE eLearning Curriculum Team)</em></span></p>");
glossary[66] = new Array( "M","","Memorial Service Network","<p>Regional systems of services working together to better provide local memorial services.</p>\n<p><em>(Source: LMR-NAGE eLearning Curriculum Team)</em></p>");
glossary[67] = new Array( "M","","MOU","<p>memorandum of understanding</p>");
glossary[68] = new Array( "M","","MRO","<p>Medical Review Officer</p>");
glossary[69] = new Array( "M","","MSN","<p>Memorial Service Network</p>");
glossary[70] = new Array( "N","","Nurse Locality Pay Survey","<p>A Nurse Locality Pay Survey is a survey conducted by a facility if Registered Nurse salary data is not otherwise available or if the Local submits a request based on circumstances in a facility&rsquo;s geographic area.</p>\n<p><span style=\"background-color: #ffffff;\"><em>(Source: 2017 Master Agreement; Article 67, Sections 2A and 2E)</em></span></p>");
glossary[71] = new Array( "O","","Office of Personnel Management, U.S. ","<p>The U.S. Office of Personnel Management (OPM) serves as the chief human resources agency and personnel policy manager for the Federal Government. OPM provides human resources leadership and support to Federal agencies and helps the Federal workforce achieve their aspirations as they serve the American people. OPM directs human resources and employee management services, administers retirement benefits, manages healthcare and insurance programs, oversees merit-based and inclusive hiring into the civil service, and provides a secure employment process.</p>\n<p><em>(Source: U.S. Office of Personnel Management)</em></p>");
glossary[72] = new Array( "O","","Official Duty Station","<p>The location where an employee regularly performs his or her duties.</p>\n<p><em>(Source: U.S. Office of Personnel Management)</em></p>");
glossary[73] = new Array( "O","","Official Time","<p>Authorized by 5 U.S.C. &sect; 7131, official time is paid time spent by Federal employees performing representational work for a bargaining unit in lieu of their regularly assigned work.</p>\n<p><em>(Source: U.S. Office of Personnel Management)</em></p>");
glossary[74] = new Array( "O","","OPM","<p>U.S. Office of Personnel Management</p>");
glossary[75] = new Array( "P","","Pandemic","<p>An epidemic of infectious disease occurring over a very large geographic area.</p>\n<p><em>(Source: 2017 Master Agreement; Article 45, Section 6A)</em></p>");
glossary[76] = new Array( "P","","Parties or The Party","<p>The Parties are the Department and the Union. The Party can be either the Department or the Union.</p>\n<p><em>(Source: 2017 Master Agreement; Preamble)</em></p>");
glossary[77] = new Array( "P","","Past Practices","<p>A pattern of workplace behaviors that is clear, of sufficient duration, and well known to union officials and the Department to constitute an unwritten rule or policy.</p>\n<p><em>(Source: Case Law)</em></p>");
glossary[78] = new Array( "P","","Payroll Deduction","<p><span style=\"background-color: #ffffff;\">An amount withheld by an employer from an employee\'s earnings.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"background-color: #ffffff;\"><em>(Source: Business Dictionary Website, \"What is payroll deduction?\" definition)</em></span></p>");
glossary[79] = new Array( "P","","Personal Protective Equipment","<p>Personal protective equipment, commonly referred to as \"PPE,\" is equipment worn to minimize exposure to hazards that cause serious workplace injuries and illnesses. These injuries and illnesses may result from contact with chemical, radiological, physical, electrical, mechanical, or other workplace hazards. Personal protective equipment may include items such as gloves, safety glasses and shoes, earplugs or muffs, hard hats, respirators, or coveralls, vests and full body suits.</p>\n<p><em>(Source: U.S. Department of Labor; Occupational Safety and Health Administration)</em></p>");
glossary[80] = new Array( "P","","Physical Standards Board","<p>A Physical Standards Board consists of a minimum of three physicians with appropriate professional expertise to make a fitness determination. A physical standards board deliberation is required when there is a question about the ability of a Title 38 Employee to meet the essential functions of his or her position. The Board is responsible for determining the physical, cognitive, and emotional fitness, and for recommending action based on examination findings. A physical standards board may recommend acceptance or rejection of an employee for continued employment for physical, cognitive, and/or emotional reasons.</p>\n<p><em>(Source:&nbsp;VA Handbook 5019/1 Part III)</em></p>");
glossary[81] = new Array( "P","","Position Description","<p>A position description or \"PD\" is a statement of the major duties, responsibilities, and supervisory relationships of a position. In its simplest form, a PD indicates the work to be performed by the position. The purpose of a PD is to document the major duties and responsibilities of a position, not to spell out in detail every possible activity during the work day.</p>\n<p><em>(Source: U.S. Office of Personnel Management)</em></p>");
glossary[82] = new Array( "P","","PPE","<p>Personal Protective Equipment</p>");
glossary[83] = new Array( "P","","Professional Standards Board","<p>Professional Standards Boards for occupations listed in 38 U.S.C. 7401(1) act for, are responsible to, and are agencies of the Under Secretary for Health in matters concerning appointments, advancements, and probationary reviews of physicians, dentists, podiatrists, chiropractors, optometrists, nurses (registered nurses), nurse anesthetists, physician assistants and expanded function dental auxiliaries. Boards will determine eligibility and recommend the appropriate grade for appointments under authority of 38 U.S.C. 7401(1) and 7405(a)(1)[(A)]; recommend candidates for advancements; and conduct probationary reviews.</p>\n<p><em>Also known as:&nbsp;Title 38 Professional Standards Boards</em></p>\n<p><em>(Source: VA Handbook 5005/17 Part II)</em></p>");
glossary[84] = new Array( "P","","PSB","<p>Title 38 Professional Standards Board</p>");
glossary[85] = new Array( "R","","Reassignment","<p>A reassignment is a change of an employee who is serving continuously within the Department from one position to another without promotion or demotion.</p>\n<p><em>(Source: 2017 Master Agreement; Article 25, Section 1B)</em></p>");
glossary[86] = new Array( "R","","Reduction in Force","<p>When the Department releases a competing employee from his or her Competitive Level by furlough for more than 30 days, separation, demotion, or reassignment requiring displacement, when the release is required because of lack of work, shortage of funds, insufficient personnel ceiling, reorganization, the exercise of reemployment rights or restoration rights, or reclassification of an employee&rsquo;s position due to erosion of duties when such action will take effect after the Department has formally announced a reduction in force in the employee&rsquo;s Competitive Area and when the reduction in force will take effect within 180 days.</p>\n<p><em>(Source: 2017 Master Agreement; Article 17, Section 5A)</em></p>");
glossary[87] = new Array( "R","","Research","<p>Research is a systematic investigation including research development, testing, and evaluation designed to develop or contribute to generalizable knowledge. Research involves the testing of concepts by the scientific method of formulating a hypothesis or research question, systematically collecting and recording relevant data, and interpreting the results in terms of the hypothesis or question.</p>\n<p><em>(Source: VHA Handbook 1058.01)</em></p>");
glossary[88] = new Array( "R","","Research Program","<p>A planned study of the manner in which public management policies and systems are operating, the effects of those policies and systems, the possibilities for change, and comparisons among policies and systems.</p>\n<p><em>(Source: 2017 Master Agreement; Article 34, Section 1A)</em></p>");
glossary[89] = new Array( "V","","VA Research","<p>VA research is research conducted by an investigator under a VA appointment (i.e., a compensated, work without compensation (WOC), or Intergovernmental Personnel Agreement (IPA) appointment) on VA time. The research must be approved by the Research and Development (R&amp;D) Committee.</p>\n<p><em>(Source: VHA Handbook 1058.01)</em></p>");
glossary[90] = new Array( "R","","RIF","<p>Reduction in Force</p>");
glossary[91] = new Array( "S","","Safety Health and Environment Representatives","<p><span style=\"background-color: #ffffff;\">A representative for the union who addresses safety matters.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"background-color: #ffffff;\"><em>(Source: LMR-NAGE eLearning Curriculum Team)</em></span></p>");
glossary[92] = new Array( "S","","Service Computation Date","<p>The date, either actual or constructed, that is used to determine benefits and is generally based on how long the person has been in the Federal Service.</p>\n<p><em>(Source: U.S. Office of Personnel Management)</em></p>");
glossary[93] = new Array( "S","","Shift Change","<p>A shift change is a change of an employee from one location to another or from one shift to another, while the employee remains in the current position and service at the Department.</p>\n<p><em>(Source: 2017 Master Agreement;&nbsp;Article 25, Section 1)</em></p>");
glossary[94] = new Array( "S","","Sick Leave","<p>Sick leave is a paid absence from duty. An employee is entitled to use sick leave for:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>personal medical needs</li>\n<li>family care or bereavement</li>\n<li>care of a family member with a serious health condition</li>\n<li>adoption-related purposes</li>\n</ul>\n<p><em>(Source: U.S. Office of Personnel Management)&nbsp;</em></p>");
glossary[95] = new Array( "S","","Special Emphasis Program","<p>By establishing and utilizing Special Emphasis Programs and engaging with affinity groups, agencies can raise employee awareness of the importance of diversity and demonstrate the agency\'s commitment to a model EEO workplace.</p>\n<p><em>(Source: VA Office of Diversity and Inclusion)</em></p>");
glossary[96] = new Array( "S","","SRB","<p>Summary Review Board</p>");
glossary[97] = new Array( "S","","Staffing Adjustment","<p>A Staffing Adjustment is a formal procedure used to modify organizations through changes in staff patterns or levels. Staffing Adjustments may impact Title 38 employees through separation or reassignment to other facilities or commuting areas, changes in assignments or reassignment within the facility, and changes to a lower grade or pay.</p>\n<p><em>Also known as: Title 38 Staffing Adjustment</em></p>\n<p><em>(Source: 2017 Master Agreement; Article 61, Section 5B)</em></p>");
glossary[98] = new Array( "S","","Statute, The","<p>5 USC Chapter 71 - Labor-Management Relations. Also known as the Federal Service Labor-Management Relations Statute. The Statute can be viewed at www.flra.gov or www.govinfo.gov.</p>\n<p><em>(Source: U.S. Federal Labor Relations Authority)</em></p>");
glossary[99] = new Array( "S","","Summary Review Board","<p>A summary review may be conducted by a Professional Standards Board when there is a question whether a probationary employee&rsquo;s performance or conduct is satisfactory. Summary reviews are limited to situations where summary separation from Federal service may be justified. VACO, VISN, or facility level leadership and supervisors are responsible for deciding whether to conduct a summary review of an employee\'s services. Supervisors may initiate requests for summary reviews at any time during an employee\'s probationary period.</p>\n<p><em>(Source: VA Handbook 5021/5, Part III)</em></p>");
glossary[100] = new Array( "S","","Supervisor","<p>A supervisor is an individual employed by VA having authority in the interest of VA to hire, direct, assign, promote, reward, transfer, furlough, layoff, recall, suspend, discipline, or remove employees, to adjust their grievances, or to effectively recommend such action, if the exercise of the authority is not merely routine or clerical in nature but requires the consistent exercise of independent judgment.</p>\n<p><em>(Source:&nbsp;VA Directive 5023)</em></p>");
glossary[101] = new Array( "T","","Telework","<p>Telework is a work arrangement that must be approved. This allows an employee to perform work, during any part of regular, paid hours, at an approved alternative worksite (e.g., home, telework center).</p>\n<p><em>(Source: Telework.gov)</em></p>");
glossary[102] = new Array( "T","","Temporary Promotion","<p>A temporary promotion is a temporary detail of an employee to a higher-graded position for a specified period of time, with the employee returning to his or her permanent position upon the expiration of the temporary detail.</p>\n<p><em>(Source: 2017 Master Agreement;&nbsp;Article 25, Section 1)</em></p>");
glossary[103] = new Array( "T","","Title 38 Bargaining Unit Employee","<p>Title 38 Bargaining Unit Employee&nbsp;positions are listed in 38 USC 38 USC 7401(1). Known as pure Title 38 employees, they are: physicians, dentists, podiatrists, chiropractors, optometrists, registered nurses, physician assistants, and expanded-function dental auxiliaries.</p>\n<p><em>Also referred to as: Title 38 Employee</em></p>\n<p><em>(Source: 38 USC 7401(1))</em></p>");
glossary[104] = new Array( "T","","Title 38 Disciplinary Appeals Board","<p>A Title 38 Disciplinary Appeals Board is a three-member Board designated to hear a full-time, permanent employee&rsquo;s appeal of major adverse action which is based in whole or in part on a question of professional conduct or competence.</p>\n<p><em>Also known as: Disciplinary Appeals Board</em></p>\n<p><em>(Source: VA Handbook 5021/10)</em></p>");
glossary[105] = new Array( "T","","Title 38 Employee","<p>Title 38 employee positions are listed in 38 USC 38 USC 7401(1). Known as pure Title 38 employees, they are: physicians, dentists, podiatrists, chiropractors, optometrists, registered nurses, physician assistants, and expanded-function dental auxiliaries.</p>\n<p><em>Also referred to as:&nbsp;Title 38 Bargaining Unit Employee</em></p>\n<p><em>(Source: 38 USC 7401(1))</em></p>");
glossary[106] = new Array( "T","","Title 38 Professional Standards Board","<p>Title 38 Professional Standards Boards&nbsp;for occupations listed in 38 U.S.C. 7401(1) act for, are responsible&nbsp;to, and are agencies of the Under Secretary for Health in matters concerning appointments, advancements, and probationary reviews of physicians, dentists, podiatrists, chiropractors, optometrists,&nbsp;nurses (registered nurses), nurse anesthetists, physician assistants and expanded function dental auxiliaries. Boards will determine eligibility and recommend the&nbsp;appropriate grade for appointments under authority of 38 U.S.C. 7401(1) and 7405(a)(1)[(A)];&nbsp;recommend candidates for advancements; and conduct probationary reviews.</p>\n<p><em>Also known as: Professional Standards Board</em></p>\n<p><em>(Source: VA Handbook 5005/17 Part II)</em></p>");
glossary[107] = new Array( "T","","Title 38 Staffing Adjustments","<p>A Staffing Adjustment is a formal procedure used to modify organizations through changes in staff patterns or levels. Staffing Adjustments may impact Title 38 employees through separation or reassignment to other facilities or commuting areas, changes in assignments or reassignment within the facility, and changes to a lower grade or pay.</p>\n<p><em>Also known as: Staffing Adjustment</em></p>\n<p><em>(Source: 2017 Master Agreement; Article 61, Section 5B)</em></p>");
glossary[108] = new Array( "U","","Union Representative","<p><span style=\"background-color: #ffffff;\">An individual identified by the union to represent bargaining unit employees.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"background-color: #ffffff;\"><em>(Source: LMR-NAGE eLearning Curriculum Team)</em></span></p>");
glossary[109] = new Array( "U","","Union, The","<p>The National Association of Government Employees (NAGE)</p>");
glossary[110] = new Array( "V","","VA Employee Assistance Program","<p><span style=\"background-color: #ffffff;\">A program established to help employees with biopsychosocial issues.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"background-color: #ffffff;\"><em>(Source: LMR-NAGE eLearning Curriculum Team)</em></span></p>");
glossary[111] = new Array( "V","","VA Entrance on Duty","<p>The date on which a person completes the necessary paperwork and is sworn in as an employee of the VA.</p>\n<p><em>(Source: U.S. Department of Health and Human Services)</em></p>");
glossary[112] = new Array( "V","","VACO","<p>Veterans Affairs Central Office</p>");
glossary[113] = new Array( "V","","VAEAP","<p>VA Employee Assistance Program</p>");
glossary[114] = new Array( "V","","Veterans Affairs Central Office","<p>The Veterans Affairs Central Office is the Department\'s main office located in Washington, DC. VACO administers Veterans programs, including the Veterans Health Administration, the Veterans Benefits Administration, and the National Cemetery System.</p>\n<p><em>(Source: U.S. Department of Veterans Affairs)</em></p>");
glossary[115] = new Array( "V","","Veterans Integrated Service Network","<p>Regional systems of care working together to better meet local health care needs and provides greater access to care.</p>\n<p><em>(Source: U.S. Department of Veterans Affairs; VHA Website, About VHA)</em></p>");
glossary[116] = new Array( "V","","VISN","<p>Veterans Integrated Service Network</p>");
glossary[117] = new Array( "W","","Wage-Grade Employee","<p>Also known as a &ldquo;prevailing rate\" employee.</p>\n<p>An individual employed in or under an agency in a recognized trade or craft, or other skilled mechanical craft, or in an unskilled, semiskilled, or skilled manual labor occupation, and any other individual, including a foreman and a supervisor, in a position having trade, craft, or laboring experience and knowledge as the paramount requirement.</p>\n<p><em>(Source: 5 USC 5342)</em></p>");
glossary[118] = new Array( "W","","WIGI","<p>Within-grade increase</p>");
glossary[119] = new Array( "W","","Within-Grade Increase","<p>A within-grade increase is a periodic increase in an employee\'s rate of basic pay from one step of the grade of his or her position to the next higher position.</p>\n<p><em>(Source: 2017 Master Agreement; Article 28, Section 1B)</em></p>");
glossary[120] = new Array( "W","","Work Unit","<p>Immediate work section that falls within a particular service.</p>\n<p><em>(Source: LMR-NAGE eLearning Curriculum Team)</em></p>");


